=== Ch2_Consent_Intro ===
Chapter 2: Age of digital consent. # diagram: digital_consent.jpg

This section sounds technical. It's actually a backdoor to the same outcome as a social media ban—but through data protection law instead of direct regulation.

*   [Explain.]
    -> Ch2_Q16

=== Ch2_Q16 ===
Question 16 asks:

"At what age do you think the age of digital consent in the UK should be set for information society services?"

13 / 14 / 15 / 16 / Other / Don't know.

*   [What does "digital consent" actually mean?]
    -> Ch2_Q16_Analysis

=== Ch2_Q16_Analysis ===
Most respondents won't understand what's being asked here.

"Digital consent" is about GDPR data processing consent. Under current UK law, children aged 13+ can consent to their personal data being processed by online services. Below 13, platforms need parental consent.

This isn't "consent to use the internet." It's consent for platforms to collect, profile, and monetise your data—mostly for targeted advertising.

*   [So what happens if they raise it to 16?]
    -> Ch2_Consent_Impact

=== Ch2_Consent_Impact ===
If digital consent is raised to 16, platforms that rely on advertising revenue would need parental consent to process data for under-16s.

In practice, most platforms won't implement parental verification. It's expensive, complex, and breaks their business model. They'll just block under-16s entirely.

Raising "digital consent" to 16 achieves an effective social media ban—without calling it a ban. The consultation document actually acknowledges this, but the question itself doesn't explain it.

*   [So it's another route to the same outcome?]
    -> Ch2_Consent_Backdoor

=== Ch2_Consent_Backdoor ===
Exactly. Whether you ban social media for under-16s directly (Q12-14) or raise digital consent to 16 (Q16), the practical outcome is the same: children are locked out, and everyone else needs age verification.

The consultation presents these as separate policy options. They're not. They're two legal mechanisms for the same infrastructure.

*   [What about Q17-19?]
    -> Ch2_Q17_19

=== Ch2_Q17_19 ===
Questions 17-19 ask about risks of raising digital consent, how to make it workable, and whether it should apply to some services but not others.

Q17 is a free-text box asking about "risks or burdens"—this is where you can flag the backdoor-ban effect, the impact on educational platforms, and the age verification requirement.

Q19 is interesting: "Is there a case for changing digital consent for some services but not others?" If you agree, you're helping them create a tiered system—which still requires age verification to know which tier someone belongs to.

